doc.ContractDescription: DURING TAKEOFF, LANDING, TAXING, IDLING, AND LOW ALTITUDE OPERATIONS, AIRCRAFT COULD ENCOUNTER ICING CONDITIONS WHEN OPERATING IN ADVERSE WEATHER. SUPER‐COOLED WATER DROPLETS OR FREEZING RAIN IMPACT THE AIRFRAME AND LIFTING SURFACES. DE‐ICING AND ANTI‐ICING SYSTEMS ARE IN PLACE TO MITIGATE THE EFFECTS OF ICE ACCRETION ON FIXED WING AIRCRAFT. DESPITE THE EFFECTIVENESS OF THESE SYSTEMS, ICING ACCIDENTS, SUCH AS THE ROSELAWN, IN, AMERICAN EAGLE ATR‐72, COULD OCCUR. AIRCRAFT ICING ACCIDENTS ARE USUALLY ATTRIBUTED TO ICING CONDITIONS BEYOND THE CERTIFICATION ENVELOPE OF THE DE‐ICING SYSTEMS, PILOT ERROR ON THE ACTIVATION OF THE DE‐ICING SYSTEM, OR LACK OF EXPERIENCE RELATED TO OPERATION WITH PARTIALLY ICED LIFTING SURFACES. ON THE GROUND, CURRENT STRATEGIES USED TO DEAL WITH ICE ON AIRCRAFT INVOLVE DE‐ICING AGENTS (I.E. GLYCOLS) WITH POTENTIAL ENVIRONMENTAL CONCERNS. A PASSIVE ICE PROTECTION MECHANISM, SUCH AS AN ICE‐PROTECTIVE COATING, WOULD INCREASE THE EFFECTIVENESS OF EXISTENT DE‐ICING SYSTEMS, REDUCING THE RISK OF ICING RELATED ACCIDENTS. THE GOAL OF THE PROPOSED RESEARCH IS TO ASSIST NASA WITH THE DEVELOPMENT OF AN ICE PROTECTIVE SURFACE. SPECIFICALLY, THE GOAL OF THE RESEARCH EFFORT IS TO QUANTIFY THE ICE ADHESION STRENGTH OF HYDROPHILIC HYDROGEN‐BONDING POLYMER COATINGS DEVELOPED BY NASA. THESE COATINGS HAVE SHOWN THE POTENTIAL TO MITIGATE ICE ACCRETION DURING BENCH TOP TESTING CONFIGURATIONS INVOLVING FREEZER ICE. THE OBJECTIVES OF THE PROPOSED WORK ARE TO 1) TEST THE ICE ADHESION STRENGTH OF MULTIPLE HYDROGEN‐BONDING COATINGS UNDER AIRCRAFT REPRESENTATIVE IMPACT ICING CONDITIONS, 2) IDENTIFY COATINGS WITH HIGH ICE PROTECTION CAPABILITIES, AND 3) EVALUATE MATERIAL SURFACE PROPERTIES, SUCH AS ROUGHNESS AND TOUGHNESS, TO IDENTIFY MECHANISMS RESPONSIBLE FOR ICE PROTECTIVE CAPABILITIES. TESTING WILL BE CONDUCTED AT THE PENNSYLVANIA STATE UNIVERSITY ADVERSE ENVIRONMENT ROTOR TEST STAND AND THE APPLIED RESEARCH LABORATORY. ICE ADHESION STRENGTH OF NASA INSECT PROTECTIVE COATINGS WILL ALSO BE EVALUATED.
